<BlogPostLayout
	title="Designing ML Systems for Real-World Constraints"
	description="A practical look at engineering machine learning systems for latency, reliability, and deployment constraints."
	date="May 8, 2026"
	readTime="6 min read"
>
	<p>
		Most ML failures in production are not caused by model architecture quality. They are caused by
		fragile systems around the model.
	</p>

	<h2>Start with system constraints</h2>
	<p>
		Before choosing model complexity, define the latency budget, throughput expectations, and error
		handling rules. This keeps design choices tied to operational outcomes.
	</p>

	<h2>Build for observability early</h2>
	<p>
		Add structured telemetry for inference latency, input drift, model confidence, and fallback
		paths. Post-launch debugging becomes dramatically faster when these metrics are available from
		day one.
	</p>

	<h2>Prefer graceful degradation</h2>
	<p>
		Design fallback behavior so the system remains useful when model confidence is low or inputs are
		incomplete. Reliable degradation beats brittle peak performance.
	</p>

	<p>
		The guiding principle is simple: optimize for stable behavior under real conditions, not ideal
		benchmarks.
	</p>
</BlogPostLayout>
